 outsiders to Danish society, their participation in religious events also localises them in the city. Written in an accessible, narrative style, this book addresses both an academic audience and the general reader interested in Islam in Europe and immigration to Scandinavia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMuslim womenzDenmarkxRites and ceremonies. 0aMuslim womenzDenmark. 0aMuslimszDenmarkxCustoms and practices. 0aMuslimszDenmark. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aBelonging.  aDenmark.  aEveryday life.  aIraqi women.  aMigration.  aRelatedness.  aRitual.  aShi‘a Muslims.1 aPedersen, Marianne Holm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610276840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102768423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102768/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles